Predicting Housing Prices - Linear Regression

Data cleaning performed in accompanying Python notebook

Section 1: choosing 10 predictors

Columns removed:
  • id: Numbers have no other meaning outside of unit identification
  • view: Just because someone viewed house, doesn’t mean he would like it more
  • zipcode: big / small does not mean better; just an ID number
  • lat: bigger or smaller doesn’t mean better
  • long: bigger or smaller doesn’t mean better
  • sqft_living15: useless for 2014 houses
  • sqft_lot15: useless for 2014 houses
  • yr_renovated: many are blank if never renovated

  • sqft_basement: not as important as other parts of house; could be blank if no basement

    • Section 2 - Categorizing zipcode

    Turn zipcode into category.

    mcchowHW2_PT1_df2 <- transform.data.frame(mcchowHW2_PT1_df2, zipcode_cat = as.factor(zipcode_cat))

    This will make zipcode a useful predictor because houses that share zipcodes tend to share similar prices. Location is a big factor (ie: near a big city?)

    R2 has risen significantly - it shows that location is a significantly bigger factor. Latitude / longitude is not capable of accurate location categorization like zipcode is.

    Heteroskedasticity test:

    lmtest::bptest(full_model)
    
    studentized Breusch-Pagan test

data:  full_model
BP = 2793.6, df = 78, p-value < 2.2e-16

    P-value is less than .05 so variance is not constant. Heteroscedasticity is present.

    plot(full_model)

    Looking at Residuals vs. Fitted, the line is relatively straight, so a linear regression model is plausible for this dataset. Residuals increase in spread as fitted values increase. This confirms Heteroskedasticity. Scale-Location graph also shows this spread.

    Looking at Residuals vs. Leverage, there are no extreme points present in top right and bottom right corners, and no points passing cook’s distance. So no need to eliminate any values because the model will not change much if done so.

    Looking at the Normal Q-Q plot, each end of the line has values that rise / fall into extremes, but grand majority of the middle line is straight. So this is a normal distribution with more extreme values than usually seen in normal distributions.
